[1] South Korea: 1 new case, 2 new deaths - MOH 25 Jun 2015
Date: Thu 25 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean MOH 25 Jun 2015 [in Korean, trans. by interns at the JW LEE Center for Global Medicine, Seoul National University College of Medicine, Republic of Korea, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323738


MERS-CoV Daily Update
- Total number of cases now stands at 180: 77 currently receiving treatment (42.8 percent), 74 recovered (41.1 percent), 29 dead (16.1 percent).
- 1 additional cases, 8 no longer undergoing treatment, and 7 additional recoveries compared to previous day's numbers; 2 new fatalities.
- Of the 77 receiving treatment: 62 in stable condition (80.5 percent), 15 reportedly unstable (19.5 percent).
- 82 have contracted the virus nosocomially, 64 have come in contact in-facility while visiting family, and 34 are of hospital personnel.

Overview of Confirmed Cases
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force has announced - as of 6 AM KST, 25 Jun 2015 - that the number of total patients currently undergoing treatment has decreased by 8 since yesterday bringing the total down to 77 (42.8 percent); 7 have made recoveries, bringing the number up to 74 (41.1 percent).
- The fatality count has increased by 2 currently stands at 29 (16.1 percent), with 1 new confirmed cases.
- Of those current undergoing treatment 62 are in stable condition while 15 are reportedly unstable.

New Recoveries
- A total of 7 patients have made recoveries from 23-24 Jun 2015, boosting the total to 74.
- The newly discharged patients are: Patients no. 15 (35 year old male), 72 (56 year old male), 78 (41 year old female), 97 (46 year old male), 114 (46 year old male), 126 (70 year old female), 153 (61 year old female).
- Discharges underwent various courses of symptomatic treatments, such as antibiotic and anti-viral treatment. The patients were cleared for discharge after signs of respiratory distress and fever subsided, and confirmatory tests resulted negative.
- Of the 74 total recoveries, 40 (54.1 percent) are male with 34 (45.9 percent) being female; 20 have been in the 40s (27 percent), 17 have been in the 50s (23 percent), 11 each have been in the 30s and 60s (14.9 percent each), 9 have been in the 70s (12.2 percent), 5 have been in the 20s (6.8 percent), with 1 patient having been in the teens (1.4 percent).

New Cases
- 1 additional cases have been confirmed since yesterday.
- Patient no. 180 was hospitalized in the same ward as Patient no. 143 at Busan Good Gang-An Hospital, and the case has been confirmed while monitoring under cohort (single room) isolation.

New Fatalities
- Patients no. 45 (65 year old male) and 173 (70 year old female) were pronounced dead on 24 Jun 2015, bringing the fatality count up to 29.
- Of the 29 reported fatalities to date, 21 have been male (72.4 percent), while 8 have been female (27.6 percent); in terms of age distribution, the lion's share of the fatalities have been in the 60s with 10 (34.5 percent) fatalities, followed by 9 (31 percent) fatalities in the 70s, 5 (17.2 percent) in the 80s, 4 (13.8 percent) in the 50s and 1 (3.4 percent) in the 40s.
- 27 of the 29 fatalities (92 percent) were elderly, immunocompromised, and/or suffering from pre-existing conditions such as COPD, cancer, cerebrovascular disease, and diabetes.

Modes of Transmission and Demographic Characteristics
- A categorical analysis on the modes of transmission of the 180 total cases reveals:
- Nosocomial infection is the most common mode of transmission at 45.6 percent (82 cases), infections as a result of hospital visits by family members comprise 35.6 percent of total cases (64), while infections of faculty and other medical personnel is report to be at 18.8 percent (34)

- Male infectees comprise 61.1 percent of the total cases (110), and females, 38.9 percent (70)
- Total distribution by age of all cases is as follows: 39 patients (21.7 percent) are in the 50s, 36 (20 percent) are in their 60s, 31 are in their 70s (17.2 percent), 30 are in their 40s (16.7 percent), while 26 are in their 30s (14.4 percent).

Isolations and Quarantine
- As of 25 Jun 2015 6 AM KST, 2642 are under quarantine with the reflected numbers being 17.5 percent lower than previous day's numbers (an decrease of 461); the total number of those released from quarantine has increased to 11 936, which equates to an increase of 726 compared to previous day's numbers.
- Of the 2642 under quarantine, 1878 are under home isolation (a 17.5 percent decrease, or a decrease of 329), while the number of hospital quarantines decreased by 132 (17.3 percent), bringing the total number of hospital quarantines to 764.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.og>

[The total number of laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection reported in South Korea is now 180, including 29 deaths -- representing an increase of 1 newly confirmed case and 2 newly reported fatalities in the past 24 hours. The reported case fatality rate is now at 16.1 percent. If one reads the daily updates, the numbers of "unstable" patients are listed, and presumably these are the patients who are in critical condition - as of the time of this report, the number of such patients is 15.

The newly confirmed case is a 4th generation case. The range of dates during which there was probable exposure to another MERS-CoV infected individual was 8-12 Jun 2015 -- a later date than previously described for other cases, suggesting continued transmission in healthcare environments longer than previously hoped for.

Of note is that Samsung hospital and Konkut University Medical Centre have both closed their services to new patients in an attempt to interrupt transmission related to contact with MERS-CoV infected patients. (see http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-south-korean-hospitals-suspend-services-as-mers-outbreak-spreads-2015-6

The HealthMap/ProMED map of South Korea can be found at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3462955,195. - Mod.MPP]

